story: Berkeley sockets is an application programming interface (API) for Internet sockets and Unix domain sockets, used for inter-process communication (IPC). The term POSIX sockets is essentially synonymous with Berkeley sockets, but they are also known as Berkeley Software Distribution sockets, acknowledging the first implementation in the Berkeley Software Distribution. As the Berkeley socket API evolved and ultimately yielded the POSIX socket API, certain functions were deprecated or removed and replaced by others. In general, they include: The Berkeley socket API typically provides the following functions: The function socket() creates an endpoint for communication and returns a file descriptor for the socket. Historically, in Berkeley Software Distribution-derived systems, the state of a socket descriptor is undefined if the call to connect fails (as it is specified in the Single Unix Specification), thus, portable applications should close the socket descriptor immediately and obtain a new descriptor with socket(), in the case the call to connect() fails. These functions are not strictly a component of the Berkeley Software Distribution socket API, but are often used in conjunction with the API functions. The following lists a sampling of protocol families (preceded by the standard symbolic identifier) defined in a modern Linux or Berkeley Software Distribution implementation: A socket for communications is created with the socket() function, by specifying the desired protocol family (PF_-identifier) as an argument.

The crash killed 31 of 43 people on board, making it the deadliest aviation accident in Sweden. Flight 267 was a scheduled, domestic service which was scheduled to fly from Stockholm Bromma Airport to Ängelholm-Helsingborg Airport, with intermediate stops at Hultsfred Airport and Halmstad Airport. story: The Kraków Uprising of 01 February 1846 was an attempt, led by Poland insurgents such as Jan Tyssowski and Edward Dembowski, to incite a fight for national independence. The Free City of Kraków, nominally independent, was a central place for pro-Poland independence activists to discuss their plans. The battle was very short, as the Poland forces collapsed almost immediately, with most of the infantry being either captured or killed by the peasants accompanying the Austrian forces. Nonetheless, in Austria, reforms were spurred by the Kraków Uprising of 1846 and the Spring of Nations in 1848, resulting in the abolishment of serfdom in 1848.

Contested over 90 laps on the 2.45-mile (3.94 km) road course, it was the 22nd Go Bowling at The Glen of the 2018 Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series season. Chase Elliott scored his first career win in this Go Bowling at The Glen after holding off a hard-charging Martin Truex Jr. who was the defending winner from last year. Watkins Glen International (nicknamed "The Glen") is an automobile Go Bowling at The Glen track located in Watkins Glen, New York at the southern tip of Seneca Lake. Denny Hamlin scored the pole for the Go Bowling at The Glen with a time of 1:10.260 and a speed of 125.534 mph (202.027 km/h).

story: The Parliament Act 1911 is an Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom of the Parliament of the United Kingdom. The Parliament Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom 1949 provides that the Parliament Act 1911 and the Parliament Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom 1949 are to be construed together "as one" in their effects and that the two Acts may be cited together as the Parliament Acts 1911 and 1949. The 1911 Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom made clear that the life of a parliament could not be extended without the consent of the Lords. Parliament had been limited to a maximum of seven years under the Septennial Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom 1716, but the Parliament Act 1911 amended the Septennial Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom to limit Parliament to five years, reckoned from the first meeting of Parliament after the election. The challenge asserted that the 1949 Parliament Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom was delegated rather than primary legislation, and that the 1911 Parliament Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom had delegated power to the Commons. Since it was passed under the 1911 Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom, the 1949 Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom had never received the required consent of the Lords. The 1911 Act of Parliament of the United Kingdom, it concluded, was not primarily about empowering the Commons, but rather had the purpose of restricting the ability of the Lords to reject legislation.
core description: The Parliament Acts of Parliament of the United Kingdom 1949 and 1949

story: The Yaqui Uprising, also called the Nogales Uprising, was an armed conflict that took place in the Mexican state of Sonora and the United States of America state of Arizona over several days in 1896. At the town of Solomonville, in southern Arizona, journalist Lauro Aguirre and Flores Chapa established the anti-Díaz newspaper El Independiente, and on 1896, they wrote the Plan Restaurador de Constitucion y Reformista. In 1896, the United States government arrested Aguirre and Chapa because the Mexican consul accused them of conspiring to re-enter Mexico and engage in revolutionary actions, but both of the men were acquitted in federal court after the United States of America consul's investigation concluded that they were innocent of any wrongdoing. Heroica Nogales, Sonora, and Heroica Nogales, Arizona are immediately opposite each other on the U.S.–Mexico border, so on August 12, when the Teresitas attacked, the Mexican consulate, Manuel Mascarena, requested aid from the Americans in or around the United States of America Heroica Nogales. On 1896, Teresa Urrea publicly denied having had anything to do with the uprising, but Porfirio Díaz held her responsible so he pressured the United States of America government into moving Urrea from El Paso, Texas to Clifton, Arizona, away from the volatile border region.
core description: The Yaqui Uprising in Sonora and Clifton, Arizona

story: The 2008 IndyCar Series season was the 13th season of the IndyCar Series. Scott Dixon driving for Chip Ganassi Racing won the first unified title for 13 years after completing the IndyCar Series–Indy 500 double. On 2008, Robin Miller reported that Tony George had offered to Champ Car management a proposal that included free cars and engine leases to Champ Car teams willing to run the entire 2008 IndyCar Series season schedule in exchange for adding Champ Car's dates at Long Beach, Toronto, Edmonton, Mexico City, and Australia to the IndyCar Series schedule, effectively reuniting American open wheel racing. In an effort to enhance full-time participation, the IndyCar Series announced a revenue sharing plan entitled IndyCar Series TEAM (Team Enhancement and Allocation Matrix) for 2008. The following open tests were held: The original 16 race schedule, which was released on September 16, 2007 IndyCar Series season, became a 19 race schedule (18 championship and 1 Non-Championship) on 2008. Points were awarded for the 2008 IndyCar Series season championship to those drivers and teams which moved to the IndyCar Series under the open wheel racing unification agreement between the owners of CCWS and the IRL. At 19 years, 93 days old, Rahal became the youngest driver ever to win an Indy-style race, as well as the youngest winner in IndyCar Series history. He also became the fourth driver to win an IndyCar Series race in his first start, joining Buzz Calkins, Juan Pablo Montoya and Scott Dixon. Teams which raced in ChampCars in 2007 IndyCar Series season stayed in North America for the 34th annual Long Beach Grand Prix, while teams which planned to compete in the IndyCar Series before the merger raced at Motegi. All participants entering other IndyCar Series races earned points towards the 2008 IndyCar Series season championship. Wheldon pulled away and led the final 49 laps to record his first IndyCar Series victory since April 2007 IndyCar Series season.
core description: IndyCar Series TEAM: Reuniting American Open Wheel Racing and Racing Teams

story: Hurricane Paul was a strong tropical cyclone that threatened the Baja California peninsula during 13 October 2012. The sixteenth tropical cyclone, tenth hurricane, and fifth major hurricane of the 2012 Pacific hurricane season, Paul originated from a trough of low pressure west of the coastline of Mexico on October 13. Although operationally not classified until 2100 UTC on 13 October 2012, a post-2012 Pacific hurricane season analysis conducted on the system revealed that it attained enough organization to be considered a tropical depression at 1200 UTC, while positioned about 645 mi (1040 km) south-southwest of Cabo San Lucas.

story: Backlash was a professional wrestling pay-per-view (PPV) event produced by World Wrestling Entertainment (WWE). It took place on 2009, at the Dunkin' Donuts Center in Providence, Rhode Island. The 2009 event was the eleventh event in the Backlash chronology. The 2009 event was the final Backlash to be held until the Backlash (2016). Backlash comprised professional wrestling matches involving different wrestlers from pre-existing scripted feuds and storylines that played out on Raw, SmackDown and ECW — WWE's primary television programs. On the April 6 episode of Raw, Vickie Guerrero announced that Cena would defend his World Heavyweight Championship against Edge in a Last Man Standing match at Backlash. In 2013, WWE released a list of their "15 best pay-per-views ever", with 2009's Backlash being ranked at #13.

story: The 2000 International Rules Series was the seventh annual International Rules Series and the third time that a test series of international rules football has been played between Ireland international rules football team and Australia international rules football team since the series resumed in 1998. The series was played in Ireland international rules football team over two test matches and was won by Australia international rules football team, who recorded a clean sweep by winning both test matches and defeating the host nation on an aggregate margin of 123–98 points. Despite Ireland international rules football team maintaining its advantage of 5–15 points for much of the match, as the Irish publication Hogan Stand wrote, "the homesters visibly tired ...Australia international rules football team proceeded to add 14 points in a charge for the finishing line. The Australians "swamped" Ireland international rules football team in the first quarter, taking a 20–6 lead at quarter time, before O'Loughlin and Justin Leppitsch each scored goals in the second quarter to extend Australia international rules football team's lead to a whopping 28 points at half time.

story: Air France Flight 8969 was an Air France flight that was aircraft hijacking on 24 26 December 1994 by the Armed Islamic Group of Algeria (GIA) at Houari Boumediene Airport, Algiers, Algeria. As a result, Air France flights to Algeria had crews entirely made of people who volunteered for the route. Air France had asked government officials if it absolutely had to continue flying to Algeria; by the time of the hijacking, they had not received a reply. On 24 26 December 1994, at Algiers Houari Boumediene Airport in Algiers, four armed men boarded Air France Flight 8969 which was due to depart for Orly Airport, Paris at 11:15 am. They had aircraft hijacking the aircraft because the national airline Air France was a symbol of France, which they viewed as infidel foreign invaders. At 8:00 pm, Groupe d'Intervention de la Gendarmerie Nationale (GIGN) operatives boarded an Airbus A300 aircraft similar to F-GBEC, the aircraft hijacking plane, at a military base in France. New information arrived at the Consulate General of France in Oran, Algeria, via a mole in the GIA: We received this information directly from members of the Algerian secret service. Just before midnight, Balladur told the President of Algeria, Liamine Zéroual, that France was ready to receive the Air France flight. Delhemme confronted Yahia to find out whether he planned to blow up the aircraft between Algiers and Marseille. The aircraft approached Marseille during the early hours of 26 December 1994. Steward Claude Burgniard said that the hijackers felt that the landing in Marseille was a "magic moment" as they had arrived in France.

story: A Colombian Constitutional Assembly referendum, May 1990 was held in Colombia on 1990 alongside presidential elections. After the murder of presidential candidate Luis Carlos Galán in August 1989, students started a movement calling for a referendum "for peace and democracy" to be held on 1990. The students then set up the "We can still save Colombia" movement, which called for a referendum alongside the general elections on 1990 on establishing a Constitutional Assembly. Following the unofficial referendum, President Virgilio Barco Vargas issued decree 927 on 3 May calling a Colombian Constitutional Assembly referendum, May 1990 alongside the presidential elections on 27 May.

story: Super Bowl XXXIV was an American football game between the National Football Conference (NFC) champion St. Louis Rams and the American Football Conference (AFC) champion Tennessee Titans to decide the National Football League (NFL) champion for the 1999 season. The Rams defeated the Titans by the score of 23–16, capturing their first Super Bowl win and first NFL championship since 1951. The game, played on 30 January 2000 at the Georgia Dome in Atlanta, was the fourth Super Bowl to be held a week after the conference championship games (the previous time this happened was Super Bowl XXVIII, and coincidentally that game was also played on 30 January 2000 at the Georgia Dome in Atlanta). Tennessee then responded by scoring 16 consecutive points to tie the game with 2:12 left in regulation---it was the largest deficit to be erased in a Super Bowl at the time and the first greater than 10 points. NFL owners awarded Super Bowl XXXIV to Atlanta during their October 31, 1996 meeting held in New Orleans. In 30 January 2000, two ice storms struck the Atlanta area within a week of each other. The Atlanta region does not receive more ice storms than most other areas of the country, and Super Bowl XXXIV was played indoors and unaffected by the elements. The 16-point deficit was the largest deficit to be erased in a Super Bowl and the first greater than 10 points. at Georgia Dome, Atlanta.

To promote México en la piel, Miguel began a tour on 13 September 2005 at the Save Mart Center in Fresno, California. In 23 September 2007, Luis Miguel gave seven more concerts in United States to close the tour, including three concerts in The Colosseum at Caesars Palace in Las Vegas on Mexico's Independence Day, and other cities like Santa Ynez and Salinas.

story: The Mexican National Women's Championship (Spanish: Campeonato Nacional Femenil) is a women's professional wrestling championship for female wrestlers sanctioned by the Comisión de Box y Lucha Libre Mexico D.F. The championship is one of the oldest, still-promoted female professional wrestling championship, preceded only by the NWA World Women's Championship that was created in 1954 while the first Mexican women's champion was crowned in 1955. The championship lineage from 1959 until the Mexico City ban on women's wrestling was lifted in Mexico City in 1986 is unclear and was undocumented for a long period of time. (the Mexico City Boxing and Wrestling Commission) started licensing female wrestlers to work in Mexico City and officially recognized Reyna Gallegos as the "Mexican National Women's Champion", based on the fact that she was the reigning Mexican Women's Champion, adopting the lineage of the championship retroactively. Unlike most championships that belong to a specific promotion the Mexican National Women's Championship was not owned by a single promotion, instead, promoters holding shows in Mexico City could petition the commission to have the champion work on their show. It is her first reign with the title, she is the 22nd champion since the Mexico City Boxing and Wrestling Commission sanctioned the championship, and the 31st documented champion overall. Later CMLL announced that she actually had joint citizenship in Puerto Rico and Mexico after she won the championship in 2015.
core description: The Mexican National Women's Championship (CMLL) - Reyna Gallegos as the First Mexican Champion

story: The Oregon International Air Show - formerly the "Portland Rose Festival Air Show" - is an annual event held in Oregon, United States of America. It is one of the largest civilian air show on the West Coast of the United States of America. This show marked the first time in post-Cold War history that a former-Soviet flight team performed in the U.S. Five months after the 15th annual Portland Rose Festival Air Show took place - on November 14, 2002 - the Portland Rose Festival officials announced they were canceling the Air Show on the basis of "the faltering Oregon and national economies would make it difficult for the air show to turn a profit." On September 20 & 21, the first "Oregon International Air Show" took place at the Hillsboro Airport, celebrating 100 years the Wright Brothers' first controlled, sustained flight on December 17, 1903. Because of runway construction at the Hillsboro Airport, the air show moved to a different venue for the 2019 show. The Oregon Air Show will feature the first all-female, "unmanned" air show in history at the 2021 Hillsboro show. story: Battle of Pungdo or Feng-tao (Japanese: Hoto-oki kaisen (豊島沖海戦)) was the first naval battle of the First Sino-Japanese War. It took place on 25 July 1894 off Asan, Chungcheongnam-do, Korea, between cruisers of the Imperial Japanese Navy and components of the Chinese Beiyang Fleet. Both China and Japan had been intervening in Korea against the Donghak Peasant Revolution. While China tried to maintain her suzerain relationship with Korea, Japan wanted to increase her sphere of influence. The troops destined for Korea sailed on board three steamers chartered by the Chinese government, and arrived in Asan on June 9. Planning to strengthen their forces in Korea, the Imperial Japanese Navy redeployed the main component of the Combined Fleet to Korean waters, since the ships stationed there at the time, Yaeyama, Musashi and Ōshima, were considered insufficient to prevent Chinese reinforcements from landing at Asan, and, in the event of hostilities breaking out, would not be able to provide support to Japanese troops on the Korean peninsula. Captain Fang Boqian received word of the Japanese actions in Seoul and Chempulo from the commander of Weiyuan, and on 25 July 1894 immediately sent Irene and Fei Ching back to Dagu, while Weiyuan was ordered back to Weihaiwei to inform Admiral Ding Ruchang of the situation unfolding in Korea. The Chinese cruiser Jiyuan and torpedo gunboat Kwang-yi, in port in Asan since 23 July, left on the morning of 25 July 1894 to rendezvous with the troopship Kowshing and gunboat Tsao-kiang, which were en route from Tianjin.
core description: The Battle of Pungdo and the Second Sino-Japanese War
